content: Nice to see you all here!
Hello RT, nice to see you
Some of you came early today, because they perhaps forgot the lesson time changes for them in case they changed their clocks 1 hour forward last sunday
renjuclass lessons go by gmt time
it is fixed time, no matter where you are.
in my country, we went to summer time, too.
now for me the lesson starts 1 hour later,
before I was also in bug hurry to make here on time
Let us now make one check,

wolfzhou, slamduk, luwenzhe, zhp3410, casar, yyfcsd, mayhem, alcore, scm2000, weigui, endlessroad, ouyang, concord2497, yun_shou, LiuJianping, strul, mcmanus, bm, callings, Silver, shuwang, liuwenming, virag, sosei, coco_yuang, sunrain, Before, Intotherenju, Aurora, Xespok.
Today I was studying some interesting games from renju database,
and I found very peculiar game.
it was played between Soosyrv and Nekrasov, in 2002 in Russian first league.
Most of you know the theory here.
the common theory is something like this:
Eventually, black wins everywhere in this 5th move.
that makes the 4th move be a serious gamble.
The same pattern comes from i8 opening.
The reason why some white players such as Nekrasov play the gamble variant is that black win is very difficult in some cases.
In fact, I might need to think long time myself, before making the proper win way.
Fortunately, in serious tournaments there is enough time to find win,
but in ORC 5 minute games I may easily fail.
I don't know Ants Soosyrv's mind at the moment of 7th move.
For some reason he hesitated to play traditional 7th move which should bring win.
Do you have any idea why?
He thought may there's a trap for him?
this 7th is strong, need to white thing deeply
so it could be a well-studied variant by N
this 18 may be giving white a chance to defend.
then black can use h11 connection through j9 and win
is that the winning way rt?
the reason why 15 is not played to g10 is,
that in some variants black needs h11 point later
it becomes evident that h11 connection is no longer necessary,
and this is the best timing to go g10
perhaps there are too many traps,
and Ants simply wanted to avoid them
and so he tried a new move.
The record in database is quite odd,
We will have a chance to judge it by ourselves.
Lets see how the game went on here.
Nekrasov is a brave player as white.
Ants finally answered to this with 9-g8
but my question to you is
Can black try any other way?
please give me your suggestions now
everybody in this room should give at least one idea
no matter how good or bad
we said, other moves except g8
ok, we have checked i8 and j8
and we know Ants played g8
besides these 3 moves, is it possible to make any other move here?
i think g8 cannot help much
white is too strong on the top now
but to try this 9th move, hoping for some balance.
These 12 and 14 moves were played in the game.
it is also a possibility, i guess.
to understand the difference between these 14th moves,
we should try to see how this variant goes
white is so strong here now.
Black must attack, or face the loss.
what is a way for black attack here?
if you say a four, then also say next move, else not helpful
maybe somewhere in the top left, but no idea
thanks for those who are active.
if you were white, what would be your defense idea?
then time for black to defence
so it seems the others only offered same idea - e7, c6
and this is exactly how it happened.
first of all, the game ended here!
the wrong result was set there in record,
announcing the game was draw, haha.
But of course, this situation is no draw,
so we need to fix the record.
wow, so many people suggest white
I expected more balanced votes actually,
because it is not easy to judge the final outcome by quick look only
black has plenty of open material,
and the resignation in game might come from either player,
so its exciting moment for us,
but before we put any stome,
who didnt speak yet, speak now please
black won or white won this game
